<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-14T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-14T02:00:00-05:00" n="851" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d851">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/8–1445: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-14T14:00:00+07:00">August 14,
                                1945—2 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received August 15—7:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1354. Re your 1205, August 6, Embassy considers advantageous your proposal
                        for use of gold bullion to combat effect of inflation on Chinese war
                        production. Taking up questions informally with responsible Chinese
                        officials would be an excellent way of ascertaining whether Chinese intend
                        to use gold to combat inflation. In view of present obscure situation,
                        however, suggest we delay discussing matter informally with Chinese. Please
                        repeat to Treasury.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>